										<p>The idea that it could be Norton is infuriating.  I&#39;ve had to uninstall antivirus software on my DELL, stuff like Mcafee, Norton, CA Antivirus, probably most of the big ones &#8211; I think Symantec is related to one of those, I know I&#39;ve had to scour that off as well &#8211; I think even BitDefender had to be removed immediately &#8211; because they aren&#39;t even good for a Windows Machine!  I mean I haven&#39;t seen files disappear &#8211; but their behavior on my machine is WORSE than what I was trying to combat from worms and other kinds of spy/malware.  I mean, these things completely take over the PC, don&#39;t ask for confirmation before completely slowing down/taking over, and then, when you think &quot;Ok, the forced scans and definitions should be over&#8230;&quot; they STILL don&#39;t give the machine back.  And worse &#8211; they don&#39;t catch MOSt &#8211; not just that they don&#39;t catch all, they don&#39;t catch MOST &#8211; of the problems!  You can still see bizarre names in your REG, and it&#39;s really frustrating.  No, the only one i found that I would recommend is actually Freeware &#8211; it&#39;s called Spybot Search &#038; Destroy.  You have a lot of options with it, it doesn&#39;t run when you don&#39;t want it to, even when you DO set it to run in the background, it has a sophisticated process of checking a few places that all viruses would have to go to rather than check your ENTIRE computer &#8211; which Windows doesn&#39;t do well to begin with.  This isn&#39;t a MAC; searching the various folders and drives on a Windows machine is laborious, and takes excessively long.  Spybot doesn&#39;t do that.  They also give you lots of control so that you can create a scan that has a much better chance of catching crime on your machine.  For example, you can set it to scan immediately upon startup, so that when you re-start, the machine can catch programs that try to entrench themselves right away and look &#39;normal&#39; after the first few seconds.  Other than this program, I&#39;d rather live with spyware than deal with true Malware like Norton, Mcafee, Symantec, or in fact any other of the pay, &#39;mainstream&#39; antivirus programs.  I&#39;m still trying to figure out how IE7, which CAN&#39;T be removed from the PC, isn&#39;t considered Malware.</p>
