			<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-91" >
			<div class="c-grav"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/41dc3e007986c35dc46763689fa93174?s=60&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-60' height='60' width='60' /></div>
				<div class="c-body">
					<div class="c-head">
						<a href='http://www.blogger.com/profile/13914828266175791354' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Herbert Barry Woodrose</a> <span class="c-permalink"><a href="http://scottworldblog.wordpress.com/2009/04/09/on-macs-and-viruses/#comment-91">permalink</a></span>					</div>
					<div class="c-date">
						April 9, 2009 4:47 PM					</div>
										<p>I&#8217;m starting to get really frustrated that there is so much reference &#8211; throughout the tech world! &#8211; of that famous CanSecWest event &#8211; and I appear to be the only person who has read the full article!  I DON&#8217;T EVEN HAVE A MAC!</p>
<p>The article wasn&#8217;t even fair &#8211; it takes 3 pages for the author &#8211; editor to get around to (in fact, he never mentions it &#8211; CHARLIE MILLER mentions) the way the Mac user could have protected himself IS TO NOT CLICK ON THE MALICIOUS LINK.  Well, as a Windows User, clicking on a malicious link is a laugh and a half.  If it were as easy as that to protect ourselves from viruses, we&#8217;d have a lot fewer problems.</p>
<p>Our code is completely laid out there.  Getting emails, just browsing normal pages, attaches all kinds of irritating programs to the system.  There are programs that start infecting my system the moment I hit the internet!  </p>
<p>Miller stated UNEQUIVOCALLY THAT Mac users SHOULD NOT get antivirus software.  BECAUSE THE PROBLEM, THE ONLY PROBLEM, IS CLICKING ON BAD LINKS, AND THERE&#8217;S NOTHING YOU CAN DO FOR THAT.</p>
<p>Miller also stated UNEQUIVOCALLY that HIS computer of choice is the Macbook, and that he wouldn&#8217;t even consider UPGRADING.  Understand what that means &#8211; one of the prizes in the contest was a NEW MACBOOK PRO &#8211; and he stated he didn&#8217;t know what he would do with that, maybe fool around with it &#8211; BUT HE WOULD NOT CHANGE FROM HIS CURRENT MAC.  He has it customized and tooled up the way he loves it, and won&#8217;t change.  </p>
<p>He also stated UNEQUIVOCALLY that the changes that Windows 7 was making to close holes was EVEN BETTER INTEGRATED in the upcoming Snow Leopard.  HE STATES THAT WHEN SNOW COMES OUT, THESE ARE ALL GOING TO BE MOOT POINTS- he even kind of laughs when he says that Mac users got the benefit of being the smaller marketshare, and that by the time hackers might consider turning their attention to Mac, the holes will be closed.  </p>
<p>In fact, in combo with his other statement, you could say the Mac will be even tighter than Windows, and hackers will still have more reason to attack Windows.  </p>
<p>Look, I DON&#8217;T OWN A MAC.  I&#8217;m only telling you that this famous Miller who apparently is some kind of &#8220;Mac killer&#8221; is no such thing &#8211; HE&#8217;S A MAC USER, A MAC LOVER.  And he states UNEQUIVOCALLY that Chrome is the most secure browser out right now &#8211; that Mac is the easiest to hack right now because Safari is susceptible to being hacked when the user clicks on a bad link &#8211; that there is no incentive for hackers to make those attacks for Mac because it is way too much work for the potential reward (he should know) and that all this is moot when Snow Leopard comes out because Snow Leopard is going to integrate the sandbox system even more than Windows is, I think even more than Google&#8217;s Chrome is.  </p>
<p>I&#8217;m still irritated that the article didn&#8217;t really point out &#8211; it takes 3 full pages, and the line is just dropped as if he was asking for a cigarette &#8211; that the hack was really a malicious link, which would have explained clearly that Miller didn&#8217;t sit down Hollywood style and just take over the nearby machine, he sent a long-prepared link to the judge who clicked on it.  That is, of course, a real world issue &#8211; but it isn&#8217;t the real world problem that a lot of Windows Users experience.  There are so many more dangerous activities for a Windows User.  Like email, or reading the news, or shopping.  The author/editor of the article in question ALSO ended up switching to a Mac, and when he wrote about it, his readership went insane.  Twelve pages and counting of hate and fear in the comments section.  He writes for a Windows Fanboy site &#8211; all they talk about is video-gaming and &#8216;over-clocking&#8217;- which for Apple users, is the unthinkable process of opening your computer and putting your greasy hands all over the contents so that your machine performs like it is on cocaine, and actually crashes and dies MORE than the average Windows experience.  Naturally, the author had to be sensitive to his reader base, and that has to be taken into account.  But even WITH that, the CanSecWest article is REMARKABLY POSITIVE for Mac users!  It&#8217;s practically an ad for Apple!</p>
<p>Especially when you take the hackers words to heart:  Snow Leopard is going to be the toughest of the new OS&#8217;&#8230; Mac users are going to slide from the relative safety of a mostly tough code, and obscurity&#8230; right into just plain genuine safety. In about 6 months.</p>
										<div class="reply">
											</div>
									</div><!--end c-body-->
