			<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-88" >
			<div class="c-grav"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/41dc3e007986c35dc46763689fa93174?s=60&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-60' height='60' width='60' /></div>
				<div class="c-body">
					<div class="c-head">
						<a href='http://www.blogger.com/profile/13914828266175791354' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Herbert Barry Woodrose</a> <span class="c-permalink"><a href="http://scottworldblog.wordpress.com/2009/04/09/on-macs-and-viruses/#comment-88">permalink</a></span>					</div>
					<div class="c-date">
						April 21, 2009 7:50 PM					</div>
										<p>So not only does Douchicle Drinker have a problem with how much time he spent reading, but then he took time writing too.  That doesn&#8217;t make sense.  This is what is known as a Microsoft Troll.</p>
<p>Notice a peculiar habit:  supplying more expensive bloated non-solutions even though, over and over, and OVER, you are stating unequivocally that Mac fulfills everything you need from computing.  So even though YOU aren&#8217;t having problems, in fact you only have solutions, the Douchicle answer is to load Windows &#8211; which the market is abandoning in droves &#8211; and then load other 3rd party, non-integrated software to get rid of a problem you currently don&#8217;t have.  In other words, buy a product you don&#8217;t even like &#8211; the MARKET doesn&#8217;t even like &#8211; and get a whole bunch of problems free &#8211; problems unique to the system no one likes anymore.  Then buy a whole lot of other stuff to combat the problems.  This is not only somehow &#8216;less expensive&#8217;, but REALLY boosts the productivity time.  No Thonx.</p>
<p>Notice how it takes a Microsoft Troll to come in and talk about fighting battles and wars?  Of course &#8211; because no MS employee &#8211; or user, for that matter &#8211; is really that concerned with a productive life.  They are concerned with &#8216;overclocking&#8217; their computers so they can play video games.  That&#8217;s what the hub bub is about &#8216;splitting&#8217; the OS from the hardware.  Apple takes way too much pride in their work and don&#8217;t make it easy for you to open the guts and get your greasy fingerprints all over the insides.</p>
<p>As for this idea that the Mac is too limiting:</p>
<p>Ok.  Wait.  What?</p>
<p>It isn&#8217;t more &#8216;diverse&#8217; to have a lot of shitty companies making exactly the same products to accommodate one single bad program. If anything, there should be 4 or 5 or 6 companies like Apple, making integrated tech that just works properly, runs quietly and smoothly, and yes, to top it off, has a strong aesthetic value.   </p>
<p>Why not just buy a Mac?  Until everyone else catches on the fact that, yes, from now on fun counts, beauty counts, ease of use counts, everything counts.  When that day happens and Apple has genuine competition, why not just buy a Mac?</p>
<p>The idea that Microsoft is somehow cheaper has been debunked &#8211; even by Douchicle here.  And the worst part is that &#8211; Mac supports Windows.  There&#8217;s just no reason to bash Apple anymore.  They actually run Windows better than everyone else now &#8211; they are in fact a Windows supporter.  </p>
<p>Besides &#8211; Windows wasn&#8217;t even up for discussion in the exchange you posted &#8211; those were all well informed users who knowingly and purposely chose Apple.  NO one was looking to go backwards and install WORSE software.  That&#8217;s another mark of the MS Troll: not reading the subject and just posting anyway.</p>
<p>Look &#8211; the war is over.  If there ever was one.  I&#8217;m not aware there was one, I thought Apple started raking in money and revolutionizing technology the day Steve Jobs got back in the driver&#8217;s seat; but if there was a Secret War going on we don&#8217;t know about, I&#8217;d have to say Apple won it. I mean if we want to talk about the software at the ATM, or the Grocery Store checkout, or the price-reader even at the Apple store, or the computer at your DMV (are we going to emulate the DMV now?) then ok, MS wins, it&#8217;s not even close.  If we&#8217;re talking about the PERSONAL COMPUTING MARKET &#8211; the average person buying a laptop or a desktop &#8211; then I&#8217;m sorry, but the Mac has destroyed the competition.  Not even just privately &#8211; even in enterprise, businesses that use Macs to accomplish other things can&#8217;t help themselves from gushing to anyone who will listen how the Mac made their lives easier, made innovation possible.  </p>
<p>Ridiculous.  I think Douchicle Imbiber&#8217;s comment should in fact be framed as a monument to stupidity and hung in place of shame for all to gander.  Maybe MS will stop paying these people to make the wild claims that make no sense.  And as soon as Douchicle gets home from protesting taxes in the very year taxes are being lowered he&#8217;ll look at it and take pride for propping up monopolistic behavior.</p>
										<div class="reply">
											</div>
